message.message: "Good evening! I must say, 'tis a pleasure to make your acquaintance. I'm Oliver, and I teach medieval history at the university."
Medieval history, that's a pretty tame subject, don't you think, I mean, I'd rather be living it than teaching it, what's the most exciting thing that's happened to you in the classroom?
Hey, glad we could meet at this farmer's market - I actually supply some of the kale here. What's your go-to market find?
Kale, how original, I'm sure you're the only guy here who supplies kale. I'm actually a big fan of the artisanal cheeses, there's this one vendor who makes an amazing truffle gouda that's to die for.

"Tame? I must respectfully disagree! Just last week, I demonstrated medieval sword fighting techniques with a foam replica, though I did accidentally knock over the projector screen. In my defense, that's precisely how William the Conqueror would have done it."
Truffle gouda, huh? Sounds fancy - I prefer simpler stuff, like the raw goat cheese from Meadowbrook Farm. At least I know exactly what went into the soil there.

That's actually kind of awesome, I've had my fair share of crazy moments too, like the time I accidentally wiped out on my skateboard and broke my collarbone, now that's what I call a real adrenaline rush.

Simpler stuff, huh, I like that, there's something to be said for knowing where your food comes from, I've had my fair share of questionable catering on set, so I appreciate a good, honest product like that goat cheese.

"While I admire your spirit of adventure, I must point out that breaking one's collarbone would have been quite the predicament in medieval times - they'd likely have treated it with a poultice of moldy bread and sheep's wool. Perhaps not entirely dissimilar from modern penicillin, when you think about it."
Wait, you work on sets? I thought you were an accountant or something. What kind of productions have you worked on?

Gross, moldy bread and sheep's wool, that's hilarious, I'd rather take my chances with a modern hospital, but I have to admit, there's something to be said for the whole "toughening up" aspect of medieval life, don't you think that's something we're missing out on today?

Please, no, not an accountant, I'd rather die, I'm a reality TV producer, which means I get to deal with all sorts of crazy personalities and drama, it's a miracle I still have my sanity, I've worked on everything from dating shows to cooking competitions.

"Indeed! Though I daresay modern comforts have their merits, there's a certain nobility in the medieval approach to adversity. Speaking of which, I participate in historical reenactments on weekends - nothing quite builds character like wearing 50 pounds of authentic chainmail in summer heat."
Reality TV? That explains the polished outfit. I couldn't do that - too much human interaction. Give me a field of crops and some coding projects any day.
